Answer: The NullPointerException is thrown because you are trying to find a view in the activity's layout that does not exist. In your onClickButton method, you are comparing the view object with the result of findViewById, which will return null if the view does not exist.

You should change your onClickButton method to:

```java
public void onClickButton (View view) {
    Button button = (Button) view;
    String text = button.getText().toString();
    txtView1.setText(text);
}
```

This way, you are getting the text from the button that was clicked, and setting it as the text for txtView1.

Also, you should remove the android:onClick attribute from your buttons in the XML, because you are already handling the click events in your Java code.

Finally, you should initialize your Button variables in your onCreate method, after you set the content view:

```java
@Override
protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

    txtView1 = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.textView1);
    Button01 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button01);
    Button02 = (Button) findViewById(R.id.Button02);
    // ... initialize other buttons
}
```

This should solve your NullPointerException.

Note: If you want to use the onClick attribute in your XML, you should create a separate method in your activity that handles the click events, and then call that method from the onClick attribute. For example:

```java
public void onButtonClick(View view) {
    Button button = (Button) view;
    String text = button.getText().toString();
    txtView1.setText(text);
}
```

Then, in your XML, you would set the onClick attribute to "onButtonClick".

I hope this helps, and let me know if you have any other questions.
